```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        string[] names = { "mavis", "senaida", "letty" };
        string[] capitalizedNames = CapMe(names);

        Console.WriteLine(string.Join(", ", capitalizedNames));
    }

    static string[] CapMe(string[] names)
    {
        string[] capitalizedNames = new string[names.Length];

        for (int i = 0; i < names.Length; i++)
        {
            string name = names[i];
            string capitalized = char.ToUpper(name[0]) + name.Substring(1).ToLower();
            capitalizedNames[i] = capitalized;
        }

        return capitalizedNames;
    }
}
```

The `CapMe` function takes an array of names as input and returns a new array where only the first letter of each name is capitalized. It creates a new array `capitalizedNames` with the same length as the input array. It then iterates over each name in the input array, capitalizes the first letter using `char.ToUpper`, converts the rest of the name to lowercase using `ToLower`, and assigns the capitalized name to the corresponding position in the `capitalizedNames` array. Finally, it returns the `capitalizedNames` array.

In the `Main` method, an example array of names is created (`names`) and the `CapMe` function is called with this array. The resulting array of capitalized names is printed using `string.Join` to join the names with a comma separator.

